is Carrier, Travis Foster, Travis Hartland, Trent Michels, Trever “Kid Vorpal” Harwell, Trevor J.J. <br>Sherman, Trip Space-Parasite, Triston Thorpe, Troy Ellis, Trust-No-One Games, Tseng, Hua-Jui, Tubby McButters, Tucker Williamson, Turtle, Twila Cotter, Ty Logan Rollins, tyler &amp; melissa, Tyler Braden, Tyler Jones, <br>Tyler Reid, Tyler Scholz, Tyler Spaulding, V . Franklin, Valentina Paggiarin, Valerie Lever, Valerio Lucido, Valerio Votadoro, Valian, Vassiliy Clottes, Vaughn McDonald, Vegar Fristad, Veronica Vandersteenen, Vespero, <br>Vicky Efram, Victor G. Balcazar Moctezuma, Victor J Kinzer, Victoria Baker, Victoria Johnsen, Ville Kugelberg, Vincent Goodlove, VnNxNeAhng, Vorgartezwerg, Víctor Romero, w. David Lewis, Wayne Bridge, Wayne <br>Marshall, Welgian Baffle, Weronika Solarek, Wes Cumbee, Wes Woods, whateley0825, WhimsyWanda, Wicked Thing, Will Godar, Will Phillips, Willem B., William Bonacina, William G Schiemenz, William J. Scott III, <br>William Joseph Bechard, William Z. Cohen MSGT/USMC, ret., WM. Downs, wookwok, Wren, www.despertalia.com, Wynter Storm, Xavier R., Xious Divinshield, Y ann RICCI, Y asmin Estrella, Y ezi Goomer, YLF , <br>Y oshiki KUCHIKURA, Yue, Yuu Gamon, Zach Theis, Zach Y okell, Zachary Alvarado, Zachary Knippel, Zachary Longoria, Zachary Stamper, Zack Holmes, Zack Long, Zak and Beth, Zalyn Harper, Zandermoore, Zane <br>Graves, Zasabi, Zeb Berryman, Zev Rothenberg, ZHULUL-N. AZMAN, Zoltam, ZombieGarou, Zsolt Kertay.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":27200000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241767,"modifiedTime":1783973241767,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"B46jGCoqD7IXcfn0","name":"Pagina 273","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>Broken Tales - Manual Básico - Pagina 273</h2><p><em>Page has no extractable text. Use the local PDF linked on the first Journal page.</em></p>","markdown":""},"sort":27300000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241767,"modifiedTime":1783973241767,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"OvDBwgjvUhW6DjPf","name":"Pagina 274","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>Broken Tales - Manual Básico - Pagina 274</h2><p><em>Page has no extractable text. Use the local PDF linked on the first Journal page.</em></p>","markdown":""},"sort":27400000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241767,"modifiedTime":1783973241767,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"A7aHHlE8cBzqsvPF","name":"Pagina 275","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>Broken Tales - Manual Básico - Pagina 275</h2><p><em>Page has no extractable text. Use the local PDF linked on the first Journal page.</em></p>","markdown":""},"sort":27500000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241767,"modifiedTime":1783973241767,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"mE0EU38YEgM0tL9f","name":"Pagina 276","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>Broken Tales - Manual Básico - Pagina 276</h2><p><em>Page has no extractable text. Use the local PDF linked on the first Journal page.</em></p>","markdown":""},"sort":27600000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241767,"modifiedTime":1783973241767,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"B1xdwvy8sKHbBpa8","name":"Pagina 277","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>Broken Tales - Manual Básico - Pagina 277</h2><p><em>Page has no extractable text. Use the local PDF linked on the first Journal page.</em></p>","markdown":""},"sort":27700000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241767,"modifiedTime":1783973241767,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"fGuXBQOCDWUndACb","name":"Pagina 278","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>Broken Tales - Manual Básico - Pagina 278</h2><p><em>Page has no extractable text. Use the local PDF linked on the first Journal page.</em></p>","markdown":""},"sort":27800000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241767,"modifiedTime":1783973241767,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"3T9bnJYJfHaL6DVW","name":"Pagina 279","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>Broken Tales - Manual Básico - Pagina 279</h2><p><em>Page has no extractable text. Use the local PDF linked on the first Journal page.</em></p>","markdown":""},"sort":27900000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241767,"modifiedTime":1783973241767,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"zZXkTY3MAfHbQVSc","name":"Pagina 280","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>Broken Tales - Manual Básico - Pagina 280</h2><p><em>Page has no extractable text. Use the local PDF linked on the first Journal page.</em></p>","markdown":""},"sort":28000000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241767,"modifiedTime":1783973241767,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"R0y7sfuMBHeYxcoT","name":"Pagina 281","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>Broken Tales - Manual Básico - Pagina 281</h2><p>Width = 216 mm<br>Gutter<br>Height = 226 mm<br>Érase una vez un niño que salvó el mundo de los cuentos de hadas. Su recompensa fue un <br>deseo. El Que Conspira en las Sombras vio la oportunidad de empañar el corazón del niño, <br>susurrándole una idea maliciosa. El niño pidió al Rey de los Cuentos que a los villanos, <br>malditos durante siglos, se les concediera una nueva vida. <br>Esta iba a ser su oportunidad de redención. Así fue como los villanos se volvieron buenos. <br>Pero toda luz necesita una sombra y, a su vez, los héroes se convirtieron en malvados. Y, en <br>ese momento, los cuentos de hadas se rompieron.<br>Broken Tales es un juego de rol sobre historias oscuras, que reinterpreta los cuentos de <br>hadas desde la perspectiva contraria. Los jugadores entrarán a formar parte de la Orden, <br>un grupo secreto que opera en nombre del Papado para investigar sucesos sobrenaturales <br>más allá de la comprensión humana. Moviéndose por una Europa del siglo XVIII impreg-<br>nada de misticismo y horror, los personajes principales de Broken Tales son nada más y <br>nada menos que los antiguos antagonistas de los cuentos de hadas, lanzados a un nuevo <br>mundo resultante del deseo del Niño Salvador.<br>En este libro encontrarás todas las reglas que necesitas para jugar. También contiene diez <br>escenarios inspirados en cuentos de hadas clásicos como Caperucita Roja, Los tres cerditos, <br>Las aventuras de Alicia en el país de las maravillas, y otras obras literarias como El maravi-<br>lloso Mago de Oz y Las mil y una noches.<br>BT001<br>Broken TalesLibro básico</p>","markdown":""},"sort":28100000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241767,"modifiedTime":1783973241767,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}}],"folder":null,"flags":{"broken-tales":{"librarySlug":"broken-tales-manual-b-sico","category":"Spanish Extras","sourceFile":"Broken Tales - Manual Básico.pdf","sourcePath":"Users\\Gamer\\Documents\\Broken Tales KS [ENG]\\Extras\\Broken Tales - Manual Básico.pdf"}},"sort":0,"ownership":{"default":0},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241767,"modifiedTime":1783973241767,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}}
{"_id":"vv6qcMjfsehZ0YpK","name":"Mapa Europa Rota","pages":[{"_id":"omo6O9jvQhZrcCU7","name":"PDF local","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h1>Mapa Europa Rota</h1><p><strong>Archivo:</strong> Mapa Europa Rota.pdf</p><p><strong>Paginas:</strong> 1</p><p><a href=\"#source-pdf-omitted\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Abrir PDF dentro de Foundry</a></p>","markdown":""},"sort":0,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241767,"modifiedTime":1783973241767,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"SksCxPGGRQFesugQ","name":"Pagina 1","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>Mapa Europa Rota - Pagina 1</h2><p>Mapa<br>Europa Rota<br>Ciudad<br>Asentamiento<br>Puente<br>Bosque<br>Nápoles<br>Roma<br>París Praga<br>Londres<br>York<br>Isla Martana<br>Sinalunga<br>Borgo <br>Maleanime<br>Valea Viilor<br>Durfort<br>Whitehaven<br>Vík í Mýrdal<br>Borgholm<br>Stegeborg<br>Malbork<br>Lohr<br>Nimega<br>ZugarramurdiVigo<br>Puente del<br>Diablo<br>Selva<br>Negra<br>Puente <br>del Diablo<br>Puente <br>del Diablo<br>HERMOSO UN DIA SOLEADO! <br>EL HECHIZO SE ROMPE UN PEQUENO CAMINO EN EL BOSQUE BARBA OSCURA RECUERDOS POR QUE? CUENTO DE HADAS UNA SUAVE CARICIA UN PEQUENO <br>JUGUETE ALGO DE VALOR</p>","markdown":""},"sort":100000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241767,"modifiedTime":1783973241767,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}}],"folder":null,"flags":{"broken-tales":{"librarySlug":"mapa-europa-rota","category":"Spanish Extras","sourceFile":"Mapa Europa Rota.pdf","sourcePath":"Users\\Gamer\\Documents\\Broken Tales KS [ENG]\\Extras\\Mapa Europa Rota.pdf"}},"sort":0,"ownership":{"default":0},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241767,"modifiedTime":1783973241767,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}}
{"_id":"9wbtpB0VVWJHyYTs","name":"Broken Tales - Storyteller's Screen (OEF)","pages":[{"_id":"ccsgfWwG08Oy9aH5","name":"PDF local","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":1},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h1>Broken Tales - Storyteller's Screen (OEF)</h1><p><strong>Archivo:</strong> Broken Tales - Storyteller's Screen (OEF).pdf</p><p><strong>Paginas:</strong> 2</p><p><a href=\"#source-pdf-omitted\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Abrir PDF dentro de Foundry</a></p>","markdown":""},"sort":0,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241767,"modifiedTime":1783973241767,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"l0Yq5gFYwzC1kcm2","name":"Pagina 1","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>Broken Tales - Storyteller's Screen (OEF) - Pagina 1</h2><p><em>Page has no extractable text. Use the local PDF linked on the first Journal page.</em></p>","markdown":""},"sort":100000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241767,"modifiedTime":1783973241767,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}},{"_id":"bMoRSXi2cEiFK3RH","name":"Pagina 2","type":"text","title":{"show":true,"level":2},"text":{"format":1,"content":"<h2>Broken Tales - Storyteller's Screen (OEF) - Pagina 2</h2><p>Position and Defense Checks<br>When a Hunter performs any kind of action, the Storyteller needs <br>to decide if they want to ask for a Check. In making this decision, <br>it is vital to keep all relevant Descriptors in mind. In the presence of <br>compatible Descriptors, some actions succeed automatically. <br>If the Hunter is the active party and acts to obtain something but may <br>fail due to an NPC or a Threat, then it is time to do a Position Check.<br>If the Storyteller’s narration includes circumstances that might injure <br>or inconvenience the Hunter, a Defense Check is called instead. The <br>Hunter is a passive party.<br>How to resolve the Checks<br>1. Can a Descriptor help the Hunter in the action? If so, 3 Base Suc-<br>cesses are obtained. If not, 1 Base Success is obtained. <br>2. Base Successes are compared with the Opposition Level  of the <br>NPC or Threat. Opposition Levels always start from one of three <br>tiers: Easy 3, Medium 5, Hard 7<br>Based on the description of the action, other Descriptors involved in <br>the Scene may play a role in determining its difficulty. When they do, <br>the Storyteller can change the Opposition Level by +1 / -1 (in total, <br>these modifiers don’t stack).<br>3. If a Gift confers Additional Successes the Hunter adds them to the <br>Base Successes; if it confers Penalties instead, the Hunter subtracts <br>1 Base Success.<br>4. For a positive Outcome, the sum of Base Successes and Additional <br>Successes has to at least be equal to the Opposition Level.<br>5. To achieve Additional Successes one can:<br>a. Spend Soma, obtaining 1 Additional Success for each point, <br>or <br>b. Roll one or more dice. <br>The two options can be used simultaneously in the same Check.<br>The dice are rolled all together: if even a single 1 is rolled, the action <br>is a Failure. Every other result (2-6) counts as an Additional Success. <br>If you use the official Broken Tales dice, Failure is represented by the <br>Wolf icon. <br>Hunter vs. Hunter<br>A conflict between two Hunters should be resolved mainly between <br>Players, with a spoken mediation between intent and outcome. <br>If no agreement is reached between the parties:<br>1.  The Storyteller determines who is the Active Hunter who will then <br>have to perform the Position Check.<br>2. The Opposition Level is determined according to the Passive Hun-<br>ter's Descriptors: Easy 3 (if they have no relevant Descriptors) or <br>Medium 5 (if they have at least one relevant Descriptor). <br>3. The Check proceeds with the normal rules; the Passive Hunter can-<br>not spend Soma to increase their Opposition Level.<br>Costs<br>Some kind of narrative disadvantage, such as employing <br>more time to perform the action or consuming a useful <br>resource to do it. <br>Possible Costs are: You retrace your steps or move away <br>from a potential goal you intended to achieve, or you hesitate, <br>avoid danger, but can’t get past what you’re trying to overcome <br>/ You get wounded or waste a lot of energy, suffering 1 Wound <br>/ You lose, break, or drop something, or waste more resources <br>than expected / Your opponent can easily move away from <br>you and you can’t do anything to prevent it / You’re forced <br>to make promises to successfully conclude the negotiation / <br>You reveal something important about yourself or an ally / <br>You lose much more time than expected / You let your guard <br>down or are caught off guard, and receive 1 Penalty on your <br>next Check / What you obtain is not whole or is missing parts.<br>Alternatively, or if no ideas spring to mind, you may assign <br>1 Penalty to the Hunter’s next action, or inflict 1 Wound.<br>Increments<br>An Increment is some kind of narrative advantage, such as <br>spending less time performing the action or getting into a <br>better position during an attack.<br>Possible Increments are: You can maneuver around your <br>target, stay engaged with it, and move in a direction of your <br>choosing, or you can easily move away from a Threat without <br>impediments / You can catch something on the fly / If an <br>enemy is moving, you can force them to stop by blocking their <br>path / You can provide 1 Additional Success to your next <br>action or that of your ally, to be spent in the immediate future <br>/ You get the best of the negotiation, impress or fascinate <br>someone, or are otherwise memorable / You can learn a <br>secret, details of a scandal, or a technique from a subject or <br>situation / You succeed better than expected, it takes you less <br>time, or you get more beneficial results / You succeed and you <br>can also help someone who is facing the same problem as you, <br>benefitting their narrative position.<br>As an alternative, if no ideas spring to mind, you may assign <br>1 Additional Success to your next action or that of an allied <br>Hunter.<br>Wealth and Possessions<br>When a Hunter asks for the availability of an item, the <br>Storyteller checks the following points in order:<br>1. Are there any Hunter Descriptors that justify that spe-<br>cific possession or that give the Hunter the possibility <br>to obtain it?<br>2. Is the object of the search easy to find or is it a rare and <br>precious commodity?<br>Interlude - Scenario<br>Between Scene changes, Hunters can ask the Storyteller for <br>an Interlude. During the Interlude, it is possible to erase 1 <br>of the Wounds suffered or, alternatively, recover 2 Soma. <br>Each Hunter can ask another Hunter a question about their <br>past.<br>During an Interlude, XP may be spent to obtain additional <br>effects:<br> ◆ R<br>ecover 2 Soma for each XP spent.<br> ◆ R<br>ecover 1 Wound for each XP spent.<br> ◆ E<br>volve a Descriptor into a Specialization. For the rest of <br>the Scenario, this will grant 1 Additional Success in each <br>Scene in which it is used for the first time. In a Campaign, <br>this effect can only be purchased at the end of a Scenario.<br> ◆ O<br>btain a Scenario Gift for the duration of the Scenario.<br>Each Interlude, however, represents a use of time. <br>Remember that the Scenario, and the NPCs, may continue <br>to act even when the Hunters aren’t paying attention.<br>Interlude - Scenario’s End<br>Occurs at the end of each Scenario or after an Encounter, if <br>the Storyteller feels it was important to the Campaign. Each <br>Hunter receives 3 XP for the end of a Scenario and 1 XP for <br>an Encounter. They also recover all their Soma points and <br>erase all Wounds suffered.<br>Y ou can spend 5 XP to obtain one of the following <br>Advancements:<br> ◆ P<br>ermanently acquire a Scenario Gift.<br> ◆ P<br>ermanently acquire an Order’s Treasure.<br> ◆ A<br>cquire a new Gift.<br> ◆ E<br>volve a Descriptor into a Specialization.<br> ◆ O<br>btain 1 Additional Wound.<br> ◆ I<br>ncrease the Soma value by 1.<br> ◆ H<br>ave an apprentice Hunter in tow.<br> ◆ F<br>orge a Bond with another Hunter.<br> ◆ F<br>orge a Bond with a Dark Presence.<br>Recovering Wounds<br> ◆ A t the Storyteller's discretion, at the end of each Scene <br>where there is an obvious moment of rest (such as a ni-<br>ght's sleep), each Hunter may recover 1 Wound.<br> ◆ D<br>uring an Interlude, each Hunter may choose to reco-<br>ver 1 Wound, plus any number of additional Wounds, by <br>spending XP .<br> ◆ F<br>or NPCs, the Storyteller assesses whether the subject has <br>had a chance to recover from the damage suffered and, if <br>so, restores all Wounds.<br> ◆ A<br>t the end of a Scenario, a Hunter recovers all Wounds <br>suffered. <br>Managing information<br>When a Hunter is looking for information, the Storyteller <br>checks in the following order:<br>1. Does one of the Hunter’s Descriptors justify the knowled-<br>ge of the information? If so, the Hunter will get it.<br>2. Does it take time to get the information? The Storyteller <br>communicates this drawback to the Hunter, who will de-<br>cide what to do.<br>3. Is getting the information dangerous for the Hunter? The <br>Storyteller introduces an NPC/Threat into the Scene.<br>4. Does the Hunter need external help to get the informa-<br>tion? The Storyteller will reveal who can provide it. This <br>can often lead to a new Scene.<br>Managing Scenes as Storyteller<br>1. Ask the Hunters where they wish to go and what they <br>want to do.<br>2. Focus on the Agenda and Events of the Scenario and, if <br>it makes sense in the narrative, let the NPCs act &quot;off-sta-<br>ge&quot; or select them to enter the Scene.<br>3. Contextualize the new Scene, describing the Place, <br>Time, and Initial Situation.<br>4. Briefly introduce the new Scene and allow the Hunters <br>to speak.<br>5. During the Scene, if the result of an action is uncertain <br>or you are presenting a dangerous situation, ask for Po-<br>sition and Defense Checks. Then leave the action to the <br>Hunters.<br>6. When the Hunters’ stated purpose for the Scene is <br>achieved or can no longer be achieved, return to step 1.<br>Threats<br>To create a Threat, the Storyteller must establish three <br>points:<br>1. Create a Descriptor that indicates the characteristics of <br>the Threat.<br>2. Establish a Threat Opposition Level.<br>3. Optional: Give the Threat a Gift to represent a special <br>ability.<br>NPCs<br>NPC Type  Descriptor Agenda Wounds Opposition Level Gifts<br>Main NPC<br>Represents abilities, <br>strengths, and flaws.<br>If carried out, considerably <br>changes or resolves the Scenario.<br>From 1 to 6, in relation to their <br>importance. 3 Wounds are <br>considered average for most <br>human NPCs.<br>Normally, Medium 5 represents <br>a solid ability to oppose the <br>Hunters’ actions.<br>1 or 2, useful to give a greater <br>insight into the Main NPCs’ areas <br>of expertise.<br>Minor NPC<br>Represents abilities, <br>strengths, and flaws.<br>Not mandatory. If present, it’s <br>tied to a Main NPC.<br>From 1 to 3. As a rule, most <br>Minor NPCs should have 1 single <br>Wound.<br>Normally, Easy 3 for common <br>examples or Medium 5 for <br>capable examples.<br>1 or no Gift. Due to their nature <br>as “extras” , most Minor NPCs <br>shouldn’t have a Gift.<br>Dark <br>Presence<br>Represents skills <br>and the characters’ <br>connection with their <br>original fairytale.<br>Representing the essence of the <br>Dark Presence in the world of <br>Broken Tales.<br>From 1 to 6, in relation to its <br>importance. 3 Wounds are <br>considered average for most Dark <br>Presences.<br>Normally, Medium 5 to represent <br>a solid ability to oppose the <br>Hunters’ actions.<br>2 Gifts, to give more character to <br>the Dark Presence.<br>Checks Summary<br>Check <br>Type<br>When is it <br>done?<br>What are the <br>Check criteria?<br>Who narrates <br>the outcome?<br>What are the mechanical <br>consequences?<br>Position <br>Check<br>The Hunter is <br>actively trying <br>to position <br>themselves in <br>a certain way <br>within the story, <br>and the outcome <br>is uncertain.<br>The Storyteller <br>requests the <br>Check, based <br>on the Hunter's <br>narrative and <br>what they’re <br>trying to <br>achieve. <br>The Storyteller <br>describes the <br>outcome.<br>The action continues with one of <br>three possible positive Outcomes <br>or a Failure. The Hunter <br>experiences the consequences of <br>the action. If consistent with the <br>narrative, the Hunter inflicts 1 <br>Wound.<br>Defense <br>Check<br>The Hunter <br>is the target <br>of an action <br>by someone <br>or something <br>(NPC or Threat) <br>attempting to <br>obstruct them.<br>The Storyteller <br>requests the <br>Check based on <br>the actions or <br>triggers of NPCs <br>or Threats. <br>The Hunter <br>narrates the <br>outcome.<br>The Hunter suffers any effects <br>and play continues. The Hunter <br>cannot achieve anything that is <br>not related to avoiding danger. In <br>the case of Failure or Outcome <br>with a Cost, if consistent with the <br>narrative, the Hunter may suffer <br>1 Wound. <br>Check Resolution<br>Not reaching the Opposition Level = Failure:<br> ◆ Position Check: The Hunter does not get what they want or alternatively (at the Storyteller's discretion) <br>gets it but without being in control of events and suffering disadvantages and Wounds. <br> ◆ Defense Check: The Hunter fails to avoid danger, if consistent with the narrative they suffer 1 Wound.<br>Equal to the Opposition Level = Outcome with a Cost:<br> ◆ Position Check: The Hunter gets what they want but at a Cost  chosen by the Storyteller. If the Hunter’s <br>goal is to harm a target in some way, 1 Wound can be inflicted. <br> ◆ Defense Check: The Hunter avoids the problem, but with some complication; the Storyteller decides the <br>Cost, which can (but does not have to) be 1 Wound.<br>Exceed Opposition Level by 1 = Standard Outcome:<br> ◆ Position Check: The Hunter gets what they intended and, if consistent, can inflict 1 Wound on the target.<br> ◆ Defense Check: The Hunter handles the problem without any complications whatsoever. <br>Exceed Opposition Level by 2 = Outcome with an Increment:<br> ◆ Position Check: The Hunter succeeds better than expected and gets an Increment in addition to the result <br>of their action. The Storyteller decides on the Increment. Alternatively, the Hunter may decide to activate <br>a Special Increment of one of their Gifts. If consistent, the target suffers 1 Wound.<br> ◆ Defense Check: The Hunter avoids the problem perfectly and gets an Increment. <br>Exchanges: conflict between Hunters and NPCs<br>When Hunters are alone or in situations where they have <br>full control and time to plan their moves, they can freely <br>decide how and when to act. If, however, NPCs are present <br>in a conflict situation, the Storyteller must always divide <br>those present into two factions. <br>After logically determining who is the first to move between <br>the two groups, each faction will have one of its members <br>act in turn until all Hunters and relevant NPCs have acted <br>at least once.<br>Numerical superiority<br>When a group of Hunters is faced with a larger number <br>of enemies, the Storyteller usually does not handle each <br>opponent individually, but limits the number of enemies <br>acting to an amount equal to the number of Hunters. <br>However, the Storyteller may consider different options to <br>reflect the numerical superiority of the enemies:<br> ◆ M<br>ake the enemies act one or two times more than the <br>Hunters, to emphasize their clear numerical superiority.<br> ◆ L<br>everage the enemies’ number to create narrative advan-<br>tages, such as surrounding Hunters, forcing them to per-<br>form a Defense Check to move, or allowing enemies to <br>take secondary actions that Hunters cannot prevent.<br> ◆ A<br>ssign enemies a Gift that increases their Opposition Le-<br>vel when they have a numerical advantage.<br>The Order’s Treasures<br>The Three Rules of Treasures<br>1. Do not reveal the power of your treasure within view of <br>the commons.<br>2. Do not use your treasure to harm a representative of the <br>Church or the Order.<br>3. Do not abuse the power of the treasure and return it at the <br>end of your task.<br>When they obtain a Treasure, Hunters must substitute it <br>for one of their normal Gifts. They can then use it for the <br>duration of the Scenario and must rewrite the Descriptor <br>associated with it.<br>How to obtain an Order’s Treasure:<br> ◆ A s Advancement during a Campaign.<br> ◆ A<br>s a mission requirement from the Order, in relation to <br>a Scenario. <br> ◆ Fin<br>ding it during a Campaign Event.<br>The Keywords of Broken Europe<br>Armors and Weapons p. 104<br>Cities, towns, and villages p. 105<br>Countryside p. 105<br>Education p. 106<br>Fire p. 106<br>Food p. 107<br>Government p. 107<br>Information p. 107<br>Night p. 108<br>Nobility p. 108<br>Order (The) p. 108<br>Ordinary people’s belongings p. 109<br>Personalities p. 109<br>Artists p. 109<br>Scholars and scientists p. 110<br>Politicians p. 110<br>Religion p. 110<br>Rich people’s belongings p. 111<br>Sickness p. 111<br>Superstition p. 111<br>Traveling p. 111<br>Work p. 112<br>Campaign Management<br> ◆ Y ou create a group of Hunters, choosing them from <br>pre-generated options or creating them from scratch. <br>Between Scenarios a Player can decide to change Hun-<br>ter. The newcomer will begin with an amount of XP to <br>spend equivalent to that accumulated by the Hunter <br>who leaves the story.<br> ◆ Th<br>e Storyteller places the Map of Broken Europe at the <br>center of the table and then asks the Hunters where they <br>want to start their story from. The Storyteller can cho-<br>ose to offer only a few possibilities, based on the Scena-<br>rios they prefer to initially bring to the table.<br> ◆ Th<br>e first Session opens with a Scenario and with the <br>Hunters intent on solving the investigation. During <br>each Scenario, the Storyteller can decide to introduce <br>one of the Clues that will lead to the One Who Plots in <br>the Shadows.<br> ◆ W<br>hen the Scenario is over, the Hunters are free to move <br>to any destination on the Map.<br> ◆ M<br>oving from one place to another takes a few days <br>of travel. The journeys are managed by a series of En-<br>counters in which the Storyteller can detail the world of <br>Broken Europe and introduce Dark Presences.<br> ◆ On<br>ce at the new location, the Hunters will encounter <br>the corresponding Scenario and, by facing it, they will <br>be able to obtain a potential new Clue about the One <br>Who Plots in the Shadows.<br> ◆ On<br>ce they discover his true intentions and where the <br>One Who Plots in the Shadows is hiding, the Hunters <br>will be able to meet him for the final confrontation.</p>","markdown":""},"sort":200000,"ownership":{"default":-1},"flags":{},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241768,"modifiedTime":1783973241768,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}}],"folder":null,"flags":{"broken-tales":{"librarySlug":"broken-tales-storyteller-s-screen-oef","category":"Sheets and Support","sourceFile":"Broken Tales - Storyteller's Screen (OEF).pdf","sourcePath":"Users\\Gamer\\Documents\\Broken Tales KS [ENG]\\Extras\\Broken Tales - Storyteller's Screen (OEF).pdf"}},"sort":0,"ownership":{"default":0},"_stats":{"compendiumSource":null,"duplicateSource":null,"coreVersion":"13.351","systemId":"broken-tales","systemVersion":"0.2.0","createdTime":1783973241768,"modifiedTime":1783973241768,"lastModifiedBy":null,"exportSource":null}}
